00:12:30,500 --> 00:12:32,000
-Yeah [chuckles]
-Look at you!

252
00:12:32,166 --> 00:12:33,916
-Hey, it's good to see you.
-You too, man.

253
00:12:35,125 --> 00:12:38,500
I get more UFO books than...
anybody in-- on the planet.

254
00:12:38,666 --> 00:12:39,833
No doubt.

255
00:12:40,375 --> 00:12:42,625
That's all CIA
secret history stuff.

256
00:12:43,291 --> 00:12:44,625
I got some Emmys and...

257
00:12:44,791 --> 00:12:45,916
[chuckles] "I got--

258
00:12:46,083 --> 00:12:47,458
I got some
little Emmys out there."

259
00:12:47,625 --> 00:12:48,958
[man speaks indistinctly]

260
00:12:49,166 --> 00:12:51,208
Lazar, 51.

261
00:12:51,375 --> 00:12:53,333
Lazar, Lazar, 51.

262
00:12:54,375 --> 00:12:58,125
Uh, but it all starts with you,
so it's your fault

263
00:12:58,500 --> 00:13:00,416
-that my house looks like this.
-[chuckles]

264
00:13:00,583 --> 00:13:02,375
Oh, I remember you
showed me a flying--

265
00:13:02,541 --> 00:13:04,625
-There it is! With the
aliens inside.
-Yeah.

266
00:13:04,833 --> 00:13:07,333
[chuckles] Yeah, I thought
that was really cute.

267
00:13:07,500 --> 00:13:09,250
[overlapping dialogues]

268
00:13:11,583 --> 00:13:13,375
Let me start this way first,
so...

269
00:13:14,333 --> 00:13:15,833
This is the first time
Bob and I have ever

270
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:17,291
-been on camera together.
-Mm-hmm.

271
00:13:17,458 --> 00:13:18,708
You know, when I first met him,

272
00:13:18,875 --> 00:13:20,375
he-- he came forward
and spoke to us

273
00:13:20,541 --> 00:13:22,041
'cause he was afraid
for his life.

274
00:13:22,250 --> 00:13:24,125
So I started trying to check out
what's on his resume,

275
00:13:24,291 --> 00:13:25,916
where he had worked,
where he'd gone to school.

276
00:13:26,666 --> 00:13:29,333
Um, started with the schools,
and...

277
00:13:30,583 --> 00:13:32,083
...it was an immediate
roadblock.

278
00:13:32,250 --> 00:13:33,916
You know, MIT and Caltech

279
00:13:34,083 --> 00:13:35,791
both said, "We don't have
any record of him."

280
00:13:35,958 --> 00:13:38,583
I thought, "Well, this series
could end right here, you know."

281
00:13:38,833 --> 00:13:43,208
And then so this prompted
conversations with me and Bob,

282
00:13:43,666 --> 00:13:46,041
and he explained some of
what was going on.

283
00:13:46,666 --> 00:13:48,416
He said,
"Look, I worked at Los Alamos.

284
00:13:48,583 --> 00:13:49,958
I was there. I was working in a

285
00:13:50,125 --> 00:13:52,625
scientific capacity on
classified programs.

286
00:13:52,791 --> 00:13:53,833
That is a fact."

287
00:13:54,666 --> 00:13:56,958
And I decided, "Well, that's
what we'll focus on."

288
00:13:57,125 --> 00:13:58,500
If he worked at Los Alamos

289
00:13:58,666 --> 00:14:01,000
in a scientific capacity on
classified stuff,

290
00:14:01,333 --> 00:14:02,458
-[sharp slap]
-this is a go.

291
00:14:02,625 --> 00:14:03,750
And so I started a

292
00:14:03,916 --> 00:14:05,750
COP correspondence
with Los Alamos,

293
00:14:05,916 --> 00:14:08,208
and they were a pain in the ass
right at-- from the beginning.

294
00:14:08,583 --> 00:14:09,791
"We don't have any record of him

295
00:14:10,166 --> 00:14:12,833
ever being there
in any capacity. Sorry."

296
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:14,708
Then we had the phone book.

297
00:14:14,875 --> 00:14:16,125
There he is in the phone book.

298
00:14:16,291 --> 00:14:18,666
I sent it to 'em.
"Hey, folks, here he is."

299
00:14:18,833 --> 00:14:21,583
"Yeah, we-- we can't find a--" I
think they called it a Z number.

300
00:14:21,750 --> 00:14:23,416
"Can't find it. Sorry."

301
00:14:23,791 --> 00:14:27,208
Then I had the
Los Alamos Monitor
front page story about

302
00:14:27,375 --> 00:14:30,000
Bob being a physicist working
there. I sent that to 'em.

303
00:14:30,166 --> 00:14:31,708
"Have you guys seen this?"

304
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:33,458
Los Alamos is a small town.

305
00:14:33,958 --> 00:14:35,625
It's not like he could lie
about it on the front page

306
00:14:35,791 --> 00:14:37,000
of the paper and
get away with it.

307
00:14:37,583 --> 00:14:39,041
"Nope.
Sorry, we don't have him.

308
00:14:39,208 --> 00:14:40,666
But maybe he worked
for Kirk Meyer."

309
00:14:40,833 --> 00:14:42,708
So I started a correspondence
with Kirk Meyer.

310
00:14:43,125 --> 00:14:44,625
This is a company that is a
headhunter.

311
00:14:44,791 --> 00:14:46,125
They hire people.

312
00:14:46,291 --> 00:14:48,500
They find, uh, people
to fill positions,

313
00:14:48,666 --> 00:14:50,500
scientific and technical
capabilities

314
00:14:50,666 --> 00:14:52,541
at places like Los Alamos Lab.

315
00:14:52,791 --> 00:14:54,875
"You have records on a guy
named Robert Lazar."

316
00:14:55,041 --> 00:14:57,833
And they said, "Yes, we do."
I said, "Can I get them?"

317
00:14:58,041 --> 00:15:00,458
Said, "Yeah, if you get a
signed letter from him

318
00:15:00,666 --> 00:15:02,791
or we can send them to him
or you with a--

319
00:15:02,958 --> 00:15:04,416
with a letter with permission."

320
00:15:04,583 --> 00:15:06,500
I said, "Great."
And sent it to 'em.

321
00:15:06,833 --> 00:15:08,625
Weeks go by, no response.

322
00:15:09,250 --> 00:15:10,791
Months go by, no response.

323
00:15:10,958 --> 00:15:12,333
I'm writing back to him.

324
00:15:12,500 --> 00:15:14,000
There's a-- I got a stack
of letters like this

325
00:15:14,166 --> 00:15:16,000
to Los Alamos
and Kirk Meyer.

326
00:15:16,416 --> 00:15:18,875
And I'm asking 'em,
"You said you had
the-- the records.

327
00:15:19,041 --> 00:15:20,250
You said you had hired him.

328
00:15:20,583 --> 00:15:22,500
You got him a job there.
Can I get 'em?"

329
00:15:22,666 --> 00:15:25,000
And eventually,
it was a back and forth.

330
00:15:25,166 --> 00:15:26,208
"Yes, we have 'em."

331
00:15:26,583 --> 00:15:27,791
"No, we can't find 'em."

332
00:15:27,958 --> 00:15:29,000
"No, we never had 'em."

333
00:15:29,541 --> 00:15:30,750
I knew they were lying to me.

334
00:15:31,500 --> 00:15:33,666
That really... is a key
moment for me

335
00:15:33,833 --> 00:15:36,166
because I knew that
Los Alamos was lying to me.

336
00:15:36,333 --> 00:15:38,083
And I knew that Kirk Meyer
was lying to me.

337
00:15:38,416 --> 00:15:39,416
And it pissed me off.

338
00:15:39,583 --> 00:15:41,625
[retro synth music]

339
00:15:50,875 --> 00:15:53,583
[man]
He says he was hired
to work at an area called S4,

340
00:15:53,750 --> 00:15:55,750
which is a few miles
south of Groom Lake.

341
00:15:55,958 --> 00:15:58,166
At S4, he says,
are flying saucers,

342
00:15:58,333 --> 00:16:00,958
antimatter reactors
and other working examples

343
00:16:01,125 --> 00:16:04,458
of technology that is seemingly
beyond human capabilities.

344
00:16:04,625 --> 00:16:06,166
Right. This-- this came
from somewhere else.

345
00:16:06,333 --> 00:16:07,708
I mean, as bizarre as
that is to believe,

346
00:16:07,875 --> 00:16:09,583
but I mean, it's there.
I saw it.

347
00:16:09,958 --> 00:16:11,750
I know what the current
state of the art is and--

348
00:16:12,166 --> 00:16:15,500
in-- in physics and it's--
it can't be done.

349
00:16:16,750 --> 00:16:18,416
Groom Lake, Area 51.

350
00:16:18,583 --> 00:16:20,708
The, uh, the installation
is surrounded

351
00:16:20,875 --> 00:16:22,208
by the Groom Mountain Range

352
00:16:22,375 --> 00:16:24,500
and there's a large dry
lake bed.

353
00:16:24,791 --> 00:16:26,416
That's Groom Lake.

354
00:16:28,500 --> 00:16:32,208
Just south of that is S4 and
Papoose Dry Lake.

355
00:16:32,375 --> 00:16:34,416
[music builds]

356
00:16:36,833 --> 00:16:40,958
The way it worked was they'd
call me at random days and

357
00:16:41,125 --> 00:16:43,708
they'd say, "Mr. Lazar,
it is now such and such time.

358
00:16:43,958 --> 00:16:45,500
We need you to come out today."

359
00:16:45,666 --> 00:16:46,916
So I'd go out there.

360
00:16:47,083 --> 00:16:49,125
I'd drive out to EG&G
Special Projects,

361
00:16:49,291 --> 00:16:52,250
which was right in
McCarran Airport at that time.

362
00:16:52,416 --> 00:16:54,458
I'd go through a
little security there

363
00:16:54,625 --> 00:16:56,666
and then out on the tarmac

364
00:16:56,833 --> 00:16:58,500
and board one of the
Janet flights.

365
00:16:58,750 --> 00:17:00,250
They were only used
by the government

366
00:17:00,416 --> 00:17:02,458
for going back and
forth to the test site.

367
00:17:02,625 --> 00:17:04,291
[man on radio]
Flight 363 Las Vegas Tower,

368
00:17:04,458 --> 00:17:06,666
runway 26 right, line up
and wait, traffic downfield.

369
00:17:08,125 --> 00:17:09,916
[man 2 on radio]
Flight 826 Ryder, I said.

370
00:17:10,916 --> 00:17:13,041
[man]
1313 straight in at Bravo 5

371
00:17:13,208 --> 00:17:15,208
and contact the ramp traffic
holds in position.

372
00:17:15,750 --> 00:17:17,750
[man 2]
Hey, cross 26 right,
Bravo 5,

373
00:17:17,916 --> 00:17:19,125
over to Rant House, 1330.

374
00:17:22,458 --> 00:17:24,708
[Knapp] Now it's well known how
people get to Groom Lake.

375
00:17:24,875 --> 00:17:27,333
The Janet planes are now
infamous, you know,

376
00:17:27,500 --> 00:17:29,666
and the buses with the
blacked out windows.

377
00:17:29,833 --> 00:17:31,625
But back then when Bob
first shared it with me

378
00:17:31,791 --> 00:17:33,208
and we made it public,

379
00:17:33,458 --> 00:17:35,791
the-- the general public had
no idea how that worked.

380
00:17:36,333 --> 00:17:37,333
We put that out there.

381
00:17:37,500 --> 00:17:38,500
Bob knew about it

382
00:17:38,666 --> 00:17:39,875
and it would confirm, you know.

383
00:17:40,041 --> 00:17:42,083
[suspenseful music]

384
00:17:51,666 --> 00:17:53,166
[Lazar]
When I got to Area 51

385
00:17:53,333 --> 00:17:54,875
off the plane and
into the facility,

386
00:17:55,041 --> 00:17:56,375
there were very few people.

387
00:17:56,541 --> 00:17:59,250
I just went into a--
a small building

388
00:17:59,416 --> 00:18:02,666
and we had to sit down
across the desk from somebody

389
00:18:02,833 --> 00:18:06,750
and they'd have a lot of papers
explaining what I was signing

390
00:18:06,958 --> 00:18:09,500
and what I'm expected to do
and what I'm

391
00:18:09,750 --> 00:18:12,291
expected not to talk
about, so on and so forth.

392
00:18:12,500 --> 00:18:14,541
[ominous music]

393
00:18:17,875 --> 00:18:19,708
The next time I went out there,

394
00:18:19,875 --> 00:18:22,291
they had a bus, a blue bus,

395
00:18:22,458 --> 00:18:25,458
which was essentially a
Blue Bird school bus,

396
00:18:25,625 --> 00:18:28,541
just painted navy blue
with the windows blacked out.

397
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:32,916
That I got onto with Dennis, who
was my supervisor at the time,

398
00:18:33,083 --> 00:18:37,250
and we drove south to another
facility, now known as S4.

399
00:18:41,083 --> 00:18:43,291
[on recording]
We're taken
by bus south of there.

400
00:18:43,583 --> 00:18:45,416
The bus has the windows
blocked out of it

401
00:18:45,625 --> 00:18:47,208
and they drive about

402
00:18:47,541 --> 00:18:50,291
15, 20 minutes, something
like that, on a dirt road.

403
00:18:50,500 --> 00:18:52,083
Every time I got on the bus,

404
00:18:52,250 --> 00:18:54,291
I walked up and grabbed the

405
00:18:54,500 --> 00:18:56,833
long chrome pole that's
right by the seat

406
00:18:57,041 --> 00:18:59,541
and pretty much just
spun around and sat there

407
00:18:59,708 --> 00:19:01,125
or close to the front.

408
00:19:01,458 --> 00:19:03,708
Dennis always sat--
he never sat next to me,

409
00:19:03,875 --> 00:19:05,500
he always sat across from me

410
00:19:05,833 --> 00:19:07,291
and looked at me the whole time,

411
00:19:07,458 --> 00:19:10,166
which was really uncomfortable.

412
00:19:10,416 --> 00:19:12,958
Now, the windows were
blocked out, but

413
00:19:13,125 --> 00:19:16,708
if I leaned forward, I can see
out the front window.

414
00:19:16,875 --> 00:19:18,875
[engine rumbling]

415
00:19:19,791 --> 00:19:23,166
As we slowed down,
I could feel that we were--

416
00:19:23,333 --> 00:19:25,708
we were slowing and turning
at the same time

417
00:19:25,875 --> 00:19:27,166
when we came to
a stop.

418
00:19:28,041 --> 00:19:29,750
When I got out of the bus,

419
00:19:30,083 --> 00:19:32,375
I can see just desert around us.

420
00:19:32,541 --> 00:19:35,416
I can see part of
Papoose Lake behind me

421
00:19:35,583 --> 00:19:37,875
and then when I walked
around the front of the bus,

422
00:19:38,041 --> 00:19:40,125
we were at the hillside and

423
00:19:40,333 --> 00:19:45,000
Dennis was by me and all that
was in front of us was a door

424
00:19:45,166 --> 00:19:47,208
and a security camera above it.

425
00:19:54,375 --> 00:19:56,583
We're going into the facility
the first time.

426
00:19:56,750 --> 00:20:00,333
It's a relatively small room
with a table and chair there.

427
00:20:00,500 --> 00:20:02,916
There was a security guard
in the chair

428
00:20:03,333 --> 00:20:05,041
and he acknowledged Dennis.

429
00:20:05,208 --> 00:20:06,250
I walked in.

430
00:20:06,708 --> 00:20:08,791
Behind him on the right,

431
00:20:08,958 --> 00:20:11,000
there's the hand scanner.

432
00:20:11,166 --> 00:20:13,208
[retro synth music]

433
00:20:22,250 --> 00:20:24,416
First time I went in there
with Dennis,

434
00:20:24,708 --> 00:20:27,166
obviously I had no badge,
it had to learn,

435
00:20:27,333 --> 00:20:29,666
so we had to, you know,
train the machine,

436
00:20:29,958 --> 00:20:32,833
but subsequent times when
I put my hand on there,

437
00:20:33,125 --> 00:20:35,625
the light shines through
your hand and measures

438
00:20:35,791 --> 00:20:37,166
the bones in your finger,

439
00:20:37,333 --> 00:20:38,541
determines who you are

440
00:20:38,750 --> 00:20:40,708
and your badge comes up
out of the slot.

441
00:20:44,083 --> 00:20:46,125
Each door you have,
you have to swipe it

442
00:20:46,291 --> 00:20:47,833
to get access to the room

443
00:20:48,041 --> 00:20:51,458
and somewhere that records
the time you went in,

444
00:20:51,625 --> 00:20:54,250
when you come out, etc.

445
00:20:57,166 --> 00:20:59,958
On the front is a
picture of my face.

446
00:21:00,333 --> 00:21:04,208
Uh, there is a big M.A.J.
written sideways on it.

447
00:21:04,375 --> 00:21:06,125
I think they're locations

448
00:21:06,458 --> 00:21:08,208
and they get-- they get
punched with a star

449
00:21:08,375 --> 00:21:10,083
where you have access to them.

450
00:21:11,083 --> 00:21:12,791
There's an employee number
on there.

451
00:21:13,583 --> 00:21:16,333
There's a dark blue
and light blue

452
00:21:16,500 --> 00:21:18,750
diagonal stripe
up in the corner.

453
00:21:19,291 --> 00:21:20,958
The Department of Naval
Intelligence,

454
00:21:21,125 --> 00:21:22,791
the stripes on the side.

455
00:21:23,416 --> 00:21:26,083
[interviewer] And the s-- the
star punch that you saw...

456
00:21:26,250 --> 00:21:27,625
[Lazar] Was on S4.

457
00:21:28,625 --> 00:21:29,666
Yeah.

458
00:21:31,541 --> 00:21:33,583
[pulsing electronic music]

459
00:21:42,291 --> 00:21:44,583
[Lazar]
It's a long, desolate hallway,

460
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:46,833
for the most part, dimly lit.

461
00:21:47,333 --> 00:21:51,000
Just a two-tone green
cinder block hallway.

462
00:21:52,458 --> 00:21:55,666
Off to the right would be...
the nurse station,

463
00:21:55,833 --> 00:21:59,000
which is just several steps
down that way.

464
00:21:59,166 --> 00:22:00,875
But the main hallway,
when you open the door

465
00:22:01,041 --> 00:22:02,500
and you look straight down,

466
00:22:02,666 --> 00:22:04,416
pretty much goes
to a vanishing point.

467
00:22:04,583 --> 00:22:06,708
It's a long, long hallway.

468
00:22:07,083 --> 00:22:09,458
And you'll have doors
off to the left

469
00:22:09,625 --> 00:22:12,250
that lead to the experimental
areas and the hangars.

470
00:22:12,541 --> 00:22:16,083
Uh, the doors to the right
will be: bathroom and,

471
00:22:16,250 --> 00:22:18,250
uh, the cafeteria, and then

472
00:22:18,500 --> 00:22:21,541
once you pass the main hangar,
the big hangar,

473
00:22:21,708 --> 00:22:24,333
I have no idea
what's past there.

474
00:22:24,750 --> 00:22:27,208
[echoing footsteps]

475
00:22:27,875 --> 00:22:30,208
There is a small medical
facility there.

476
00:22:30,541 --> 00:22:35,000
Uh, it's the only female I saw,
ever, in the facility.

477
00:22:35,166 --> 00:22:37,958
She explained that we are
potentially working with

478
00:22:38,125 --> 00:22:40,041
a lot of unknown materials

479
00:22:40,416 --> 00:22:43,958
and there could be sensitivities
or allergic reactions to them.

480
00:22:44,208 --> 00:22:48,291
So she drew a small grid on the
bottom of my arm

481
00:22:48,458 --> 00:22:51,291
and had a variety of

482
00:22:51,625 --> 00:22:54,541
small needles with different
substances on them and

483
00:22:54,708 --> 00:22:58,750
pricked a little area inside
each one of those squares,

484
00:22:59,166 --> 00:23:03,125
uh, just to see, you know, if
I'd have any reaction to them.

485
00:23:03,750 --> 00:23:06,333
I was also instructed
to drink this

486
00:23:06,500 --> 00:23:08,458
liquid that I said
smelled like pine.

487
00:23:09,125 --> 00:23:11,541
It's kind of an amber-colored
liquid, if I recall.

488
00:23:11,791 --> 00:23:15,333
And, it did give me a reaction
that that evening,

489
00:23:15,500 --> 00:23:17,000
I think I had stomach cramps.

490
00:23:17,166 --> 00:23:20,250
But, I can't really say
that caused them.

491
00:23:20,500 --> 00:23:22,125
You know, it's coincidental, so.

492
00:23:22,291 --> 00:23:24,958
But I-- [chuckles] I can't
officially blame it on that.

493
00:23:25,875 --> 00:23:27,875
[electronic pulsing]

494
00:23:33,875 --> 00:23:35,458
When I first began at S4,

495
00:23:35,625 --> 00:23:37,583
I would randomly be taken
into a small room,

496
00:23:37,833 --> 00:23:39,250
which contained
a table, a chair,

497
00:23:39,416 --> 00:23:41,833
and 120 or so briefings
in blue folders.

498
00:23:42,500 --> 00:23:45,833
These reports appeared to be an
overview of alien information,

499
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:48,166
which could be used to brief
scientists from any field

500
00:23:48,333 --> 00:23:49,958
about the scope
of the whole project,

501
00:23:50,125 --> 00:23:52,291
and not just their specific
field of endeavor.

502
00:23:52,458 --> 00:23:55,291
The file on top was
Project Galileo.

503
00:23:55,541 --> 00:23:58,750
And as it turned out, that's
the project that I was part of.

504
00:23:59,083 --> 00:24:03,375
And that clearly... referred
to reverse engineering

505
00:24:03,541 --> 00:24:06,166
a recovered alien spacecraft.

506
00:24:06,708 --> 00:24:09,916
My job in this program was to
be part of a back engineering
team.

507
00:24:10,375 --> 00:24:12,791
Back engineering is the act of
taking a finished product

508
00:24:12,958 --> 00:24:15,166
and tearing it apart to find
out what makes it tick.

509
00:24:15,791 --> 00:24:17,625
The goal in this program
was to see

510
00:24:17,791 --> 00:24:19,125
if the technology of the disc

511
00:24:19,291 --> 00:24:21,291
could be duplicated with
Earth materials.

512
00:24:23,083 --> 00:24:24,958
Dennis brought us into the lab.
He said,

513
00:24:25,125 --> 00:24:27,375
"This is where you're gonna
be spending most of your time."

514
00:24:28,125 --> 00:24:30,250
I can see it was a...
typical lab setup.

515
00:24:30,416 --> 00:24:33,333
There was stuff, components,
everything all over the place.

516
00:24:33,500 --> 00:24:35,416
And one guy in there,
Barry, who--

517
00:24:35,583 --> 00:24:37,375
who got up immediately and was

518
00:24:37,541 --> 00:24:39,750
clearly really happy to see me.

519
00:24:40,500 --> 00:24:43,166
It seems like he used to work
with somebody else.

520
00:24:43,333 --> 00:24:45,250
He had a lot to say,
he was excited

521
00:24:45,500 --> 00:24:48,083
to show me everything and
bring me up to speed.

522
00:24:48,250 --> 00:24:50,208
It was kind of like a
little kid at that point.

523
00:24:50,375 --> 00:24:51,500
"Wait till you see this."

524
00:24:51,666 --> 00:24:53,125
And, you know, he'd display

525
00:24:53,291 --> 00:24:54,916
how the amplifier,

526
00:24:55,083 --> 00:24:57,708
you know, operates connected
to the emitters and

527
00:24:57,875 --> 00:25:01,041
how things operate, even though
they're not connected, and--

528
00:25:01,375 --> 00:25:05,083
But yeah, he was... very anxious
to show me everything

529
00:25:05,250 --> 00:25:07,583
and anxious to make
some progress too.

530
00:25:07,750 --> 00:25:09,791
[retro synth music]

531
00:25:13,041 --> 00:25:14,666
So this is where he said,

532
00:25:15,291 --> 00:25:17,458
"We're focusing primarily on the

533
00:25:17,625 --> 00:25:19,583
power and propulsion system
of the craft."

534
00:25:20,166 --> 00:25:22,333
And I said, "Great,

535
00:25:22,875 --> 00:25:25,083
w-- what... craft?"

536
00:25:25,791 --> 00:25:28,250
I think he was holding off
intentionally,

537
00:25:28,416 --> 00:25:31,791
telling me anything, because
what he wanted me to do

538
00:25:32,041 --> 00:25:35,000
was to feel the gravitational
field on the reactor.

539
00:25:35,750 --> 00:25:39,958
So he went over, he rotated the
emitter and the reactor was on.

540
00:25:40,125 --> 00:25:42,041
He said, "Go ahead and
try and touch that."

541
00:25:42,541 --> 00:25:44,416
And when I pushed
my hands on it,

542
00:25:45,041 --> 00:25:49,250
that was the biggest
scientific shock I'd ever had

543
00:25:49,583 --> 00:25:53,666
because there's nothing
in the world that can do that.

544
00:25:54,375 --> 00:25:57,541
And he said, "That's what
propels the craft.

545
00:25:58,041 --> 00:26:00,541
And that is a gravity
generator."

546
00:26:01,166 --> 00:26:04,958
And that... was
the moment that...

547
00:26:05,500 --> 00:26:08,333
I realized [chuckles]
what was going on.

548
00:26:09,375 --> 00:26:13,625
Barry indicated that
what I saw there was

549
00:26:13,791 --> 00:26:16,166
the propulsion system
in its entirety.

550
00:26:17,875 --> 00:26:20,000
He started with the reactor and

551
00:26:20,166 --> 00:26:22,166
the small hemisphere
on the plate.

552
00:26:22,333 --> 00:26:25,000
said, "This is apparently
the power source."

553
00:26:25,166 --> 00:26:27,250
To the left of that
on the ground

554
00:26:27,416 --> 00:26:30,500
was what he referred to
as the amplifier.

555
00:26:30,666 --> 00:26:32,250
And to the left of that

556
00:26:32,416 --> 00:26:36,625
at 90 degrees, was a large pipe
looking object.

557
00:26:36,791 --> 00:26:38,333
He said that was the emitter.

558
00:26:39,375 --> 00:26:41,375
These function together
to produce

559
00:26:41,541 --> 00:26:43,416
a gravity propulsion system.

560
00:26:43,583 --> 00:26:47,125
The power base frequency was
created by the reactor.

561
00:26:47,375 --> 00:26:50,291
The amplifier increased
its amplitude

562
00:26:50,500 --> 00:26:52,541
and that was channeled
into the emitter

563
00:26:52,708 --> 00:26:54,583
and focused or beamed,

564
00:26:54,750 --> 00:26:57,416
wherever you want to
provide the propulsion.

565
00:26:57,708 --> 00:27:01,333
Barry shut the system off
by rotating the emitter

566
00:27:01,625 --> 00:27:04,500
and then he proceeded to
take apart the reactor to

567
00:27:04,666 --> 00:27:06,375
show me it had components too.

568
00:27:06,666 --> 00:27:08,250
When he did that,
you were able to touch

569
00:27:08,416 --> 00:27:10,000
the hemisphere in the reactor,

570
00:27:10,625 --> 00:27:13,583
remove the hemisphere and then
you can see a small tower

571
00:27:13,750 --> 00:27:15,333
with a tube coming off of it.

572
00:27:15,875 --> 00:27:17,833
That tower had a cap on it.

573
00:27:18,458 --> 00:27:21,541
The cap slid off and inside...

574
00:27:22,083 --> 00:27:24,166
was a triangular
piece of a...

575
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:27,750
...almost copper-colored...
material.

576
00:27:29,041 --> 00:27:31,208
It had little slice marks on it

577
00:27:31,541 --> 00:27:34,625
and that material turned out to
be element 115,

578
00:27:34,791 --> 00:27:38,583
a super heavy element yet
to be discovered at the time.

579
00:27:38,750 --> 00:27:40,083
To start up the reactor,
of course,

580
00:27:40,250 --> 00:27:42,000
we need some element 115.

581
00:27:42,166 --> 00:27:44,791
In fact, you need 223 grams,
which is just

582
00:27:44,958 --> 00:27:48,291
under half a pound, machined
into a wedge like this.

583
00:27:49,125 --> 00:27:52,333
And a piece of 115 this size
can be utilized as fuel

584
00:27:52,500 --> 00:27:54,583
for a period of 20 to 30 years.

585
00:27:55,083 --> 00:27:58,958
Element 115's melting point
is 1740 degrees Celsius

586
00:27:59,125 --> 00:28:01,583
and its standard oxidation
state is plus 3.

587
00:28:02,083 --> 00:28:05,708
The atomic radius of 115
is 1.87 angstroms.

588
00:28:06,208 --> 00:28:08,791
The frequency of the carrier
wave for element 115's

589
00:28:08,958 --> 00:28:12,958
gravity A wave is 7.46 hertz
at a one micron bandwidth.

590
00:28:16,416 --> 00:28:18,625
This is the reactor,
and from what

591
00:28:18,791 --> 00:28:21,875
we've been able to determine,
it's what powers the craft.

592
00:28:22,375 --> 00:28:24,000
It's made of several components.

593
00:28:25,083 --> 00:28:26,791
First is a removable hemisphere.

594
00:28:28,875 --> 00:28:30,041
There's a tower,

595
00:28:30,583 --> 00:28:32,500
and we'll call
our drift tube on the side,

596
00:28:32,666 --> 00:28:33,875
a small cap,

597
00:28:34,625 --> 00:28:35,750
that comes off,

598
00:28:36,208 --> 00:28:38,041
and inside the tower...

599
00:28:39,791 --> 00:28:43,166
...is what we think is the fuel,
element 115.

600
00:28:44,125 --> 00:28:46,916
The fuel element is placed
inside the tower,

601
00:28:48,250 --> 00:28:49,750
cap is placed on,

602
00:28:51,250 --> 00:28:54,125
and then, as soon as the
hemisphere

603
00:28:54,750 --> 00:28:57,083
makes a flat connection
to the base,

604
00:28:57,958 --> 00:29:00,000
it'll create its own
gravitational field.

605
00:29:00,166 --> 00:29:01,333
It becomes operational.

606
00:29:01,500 --> 00:29:02,916
It will push your hands away

607
00:29:03,125 --> 00:29:04,833
as soon as that's sat on there.

608
00:29:05,291 --> 00:29:10,083
And the field is--
feels similar to... uh,

609
00:29:10,416 --> 00:29:12,166
like poles of a magnet.

610
00:29:12,333 --> 00:29:14,166
There's some elasticity to it.

611
00:29:14,750 --> 00:29:17,958
You could push back on it
as hard as you want,

612
00:29:18,125 --> 00:29:20,750
but-- and a--
a really important thing is

613
00:29:20,916 --> 00:29:24,833
it's not transferring that force
to the base.

614
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:26,583
Even though this would move,

615
00:29:27,833 --> 00:29:29,500
you can push on the field

616
00:29:29,875 --> 00:29:31,333
and it wouldn't slide this.

617
00:29:31,500 --> 00:29:33,750
I mean, if you had two magnets
with like poles

618
00:29:33,916 --> 00:29:36,541
and you pushed on one,
the other one would go
sliding across the table.

619
00:29:36,708 --> 00:29:38,208
That doesn't happen here.

620
00:29:39,041 --> 00:29:40,875
Through X-rays,
we were able to determine

621
00:29:41,041 --> 00:29:42,625
that there's a hollow tube

622
00:29:43,125 --> 00:29:45,000
that goes around the base.

623
00:29:45,375 --> 00:29:47,666
We assume that's something
like a cyclotron,

624
00:29:48,583 --> 00:29:50,958
where particles are
accelerated around

625
00:29:51,125 --> 00:29:53,291
and there's, if you wanna
call it an off ramp,

626
00:29:54,083 --> 00:29:57,666
is the drift tube, comes up
and interacts in the tower

627
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:00,333
in some way to produce energy.

628
00:30:00,625 --> 00:30:03,916
Now, this device doesn't produce
any heat at all.

629
00:30:04,125 --> 00:30:08,375
It didn't produce one degree...
of temperature change,

630
00:30:08,541 --> 00:30:10,541
no matter how much load
it was under.

631
00:30:10,833 --> 00:30:12,291
To turn the reactor on...

632
00:30:13,250 --> 00:30:15,333
...the-- all the components
in the craft

633
00:30:15,500 --> 00:30:16,958
are connected in some way,

634
00:30:17,125 --> 00:30:18,500
but not physically.

635
00:30:18,875 --> 00:30:21,666
And we really don't know
how that is.

636
00:30:22,333 --> 00:30:25,458
Um, if you take one
of the emitters

637
00:30:25,625 --> 00:30:27,625
and you rotate it
past 20 degrees,

638
00:30:27,916 --> 00:30:29,333
the reactor will turn on,

639
00:30:30,208 --> 00:30:32,500
and you can no longer even
get your hands by it.

640
00:30:33,208 --> 00:30:37,250
Conversely, to turn it off,
rotate... the emitter,

641
00:30:37,583 --> 00:30:38,833
the reactor shuts down.

642
00:30:39,458 --> 00:30:42,375
And assuming that's removing the
load from the reactor,

643
00:30:42,541 --> 00:30:44,083
I think it's just load sensing.

644
00:30:44,250 --> 00:30:47,041
It sees that the emitter and
amplifier wants power

645
00:30:47,333 --> 00:30:49,583
and it turns on, but
the exact mechanism

646
00:30:49,750 --> 00:30:52,416
that's taking place there is--
is completely unknown.

647
00:30:53,041 --> 00:30:56,083
So I began to feel the field
about up here.

648
00:30:57,041 --> 00:30:59,666
And at-- at this distance,
there's--

649
00:30:59,833 --> 00:31:02,541
y-- there's no way you're moving
your hands any closer.

650
00:31:03,916 --> 00:31:06,958
But, uh-- I guess the most
amazing thing is

651
00:31:07,208 --> 00:31:10,250
leaning into it,
putting all your force on that,

652
00:31:10,458 --> 00:31:12,375
no-- nothing moves at all.

653
00:31:12,833 --> 00:31:16,083
And when the reactor's off,
you can easily slide it.

654
00:31:16,416 --> 00:31:19,500
You know, so, that's--
that's really impressive.

655
00:31:20,250 --> 00:31:24,583
We call this a gravity propelled
craft, a gravity generator.

656
00:31:24,958 --> 00:31:27,541
And we're calling it
that because,

657
00:31:27,916 --> 00:31:30,041
we know what--
we know the effects of gravity.

658
00:31:30,666 --> 00:31:31,916
We know how it works.

659
00:31:32,416 --> 00:31:35,125
Um, we don't know everything
about it, but...

660
00:31:36,041 --> 00:31:38,375
...this produces an effect
similar to gravity.

661
00:31:38,541 --> 00:31:39,708
So we're calling it that

662
00:31:39,875 --> 00:31:41,875
because we don't know of
any other forces

663
00:31:42,416 --> 00:31:43,583
that exist like that.

664
00:31:43,791 --> 00:31:45,583
This could, of course, be

665
00:31:45,750 --> 00:31:47,375
something other than gravity.

666
00:31:47,541 --> 00:31:49,166
This could be a completely
other force

667
00:31:49,333 --> 00:31:51,000
that we're just not
familiar with.

668
00:31:51,166 --> 00:31:53,791
And we're just labeling it,
you know, as gravity propulsion,

669
00:31:53,958 --> 00:31:56,916
a gravity field coming
off of here, uh,

670
00:31:57,083 --> 00:31:58,875
just because that's all
we're familiar with.

671
00:31:59,208 --> 00:32:00,583
Um, but...

672
00:32:01,208 --> 00:32:02,375
keeping that in mind,

673
00:32:02,541 --> 00:32:03,916
we tried to see if it was

674
00:32:04,083 --> 00:32:05,416
possible to shield it

675
00:32:05,875 --> 00:32:08,000
with, uh, different materials.

676
00:32:08,166 --> 00:32:12,333
You know, we tried cardboard,
plastic, metal, everything.

677
00:32:12,500 --> 00:32:14,541
And the field-- Eh--

678
00:32:14,708 --> 00:32:16,833
The field
interacts with everything.

679
00:32:17,166 --> 00:32:20,583
Um, and there's nothing really
that shields it.

680
00:32:21,083 --> 00:32:22,958
So... um...

681
00:32:23,541 --> 00:32:25,500
You know, it's-- again, it
behaves like

682
00:32:25,666 --> 00:32:27,250
gravity does, but...

683
00:32:28,166 --> 00:32:29,916
...it could certainly be
something else.

684
00:32:30,291 --> 00:32:32,291
[suspenseful music]

685
00:32:32,458 --> 00:32:35,291
Part of the fear was based
in the fact that

686
00:32:35,458 --> 00:32:37,791
they had said I was
replacing somebody

687
00:32:37,958 --> 00:32:39,458
that was killed in the project.

688
00:32:39,958 --> 00:32:43,583
They were being pressed to
produce some results.

689
00:32:44,333 --> 00:32:46,833
And, I think,
from what I understand,

690
00:32:47,250 --> 00:32:49,833
-they cut into an
operating reactor
-[torch hissing]

691
00:32:50,000 --> 00:32:51,625
-[loud explosion]
-and it detonated.

692
00:32:56,250 --> 00:32:57,666
It's not like it was a--

693
00:32:58,291 --> 00:33:00,708
you know, a research project
where you're--

694
00:33:01,041 --> 00:33:02,375
you're really into it.

695
00:33:02,708 --> 00:33:06,250
It was-- it was exactly like
disarming a bomb...

696
00:33:07,250 --> 00:33:08,333
...every single day.

697
00:33:08,750 --> 00:33:11,000
That's what it was like,
because, a-- once again,

698
00:33:11,166 --> 00:33:13,083
we had no idea what
we were working with.

699
00:33:13,250 --> 00:33:16,750
And we were working with
absolutely tremendous

700
00:33:16,916 --> 00:33:18,666
amounts of energy,

701
00:33:18,833 --> 00:33:22,458
tremendous amounts of power,
in very condensed sources.

702
00:33:22,833 --> 00:33:24,166
The slightest wrong move

703
00:33:24,333 --> 00:33:26,333
could release a tremendous
amount of energy.

704
00:33:28,208 --> 00:33:29,375
[music fades]

705
00:33:30,416 --> 00:33:32,250
[ominous sci-fi music]

706
00:33:32,625 --> 00:33:34,625
So as part of our investigation,

707
00:33:34,791 --> 00:33:36,708
we go through all the
normal protocols.

708
00:33:36,875 --> 00:33:39,000
We contact the U.S. Air Force
at Nellis.

709
00:33:39,166 --> 00:33:41,166
I'm asking questions
about Area 51.

710
00:33:41,333 --> 00:33:42,791
They won't answer any.

711
00:33:42,958 --> 00:33:45,625
Um, later on, I asked them
about a place called S4.

712
00:33:45,791 --> 00:33:47,708
I called the
Nellis Air Force Base,

713
00:33:47,875 --> 00:33:49,833
with their public
information office,

714
00:33:50,041 --> 00:33:51,875
somebody I had got to know
over the years,

715
00:33:52,041 --> 00:33:54,250
"Do you have any place
called S4

716
00:33:54,583 --> 00:33:55,541
on the Nellis Range?"

717
00:33:55,708 --> 00:33:57,083
And the answer was yes.

718
00:33:57,291 --> 00:33:59,041
And in fact, they said
there's more than one.

719
00:33:59,541 --> 00:34:01,583
I said "Can you tell us
where it is?" "No."

720
00:34:01,833 --> 00:34:03,916
"Can you tell us
what goes on there?" "No."

721
00:34:04,666 --> 00:34:06,041
"But it's real?" "Yes."

722
00:34:06,208 --> 00:34:07,625
And I asked them about
Papoose Lake.

723
00:34:07,791 --> 00:34:09,583
"You got anything there?"
"No. Absolutely not."

724
00:34:09,750 --> 00:34:13,166
"Nothing, ever." And I'd asked
people who worked out there,

725
00:34:13,416 --> 00:34:16,958
anything at S4,
Papoose Lake. "Never, ever.

726
00:34:17,541 --> 00:34:19,750
We don't even have a way to get
there. There's nothing there."

727
00:34:20,333 --> 00:34:21,791
I knew that was not true.

728
00:34:22,041 --> 00:34:23,875
You know, we eventually got
some satellite photos

729
00:34:24,041 --> 00:34:26,958
that showed us there's a road
from Groom down to Papoose.

730
00:34:27,250 --> 00:34:28,833
Why do you build a
road down there to

731
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:31,625
a place that doesn't exist
and there's nothing there?

732
00:34:31,791 --> 00:34:34,083
The S4 installation is built
into the mountain,

733
00:34:34,250 --> 00:34:36,041
and the hangar doors are
built on an angle

734
00:34:36,208 --> 00:34:38,041
commensurate with
the slope of the mountain.

735
00:34:38,333 --> 00:34:40,708
These doors are covered with
a sand textured coating

736
00:34:40,875 --> 00:34:43,500
to blend in with the side
of the mountain and
the desert floor.

737
00:34:43,958 --> 00:34:45,833
-So here's the entrance,
right here.
-Okay.

738
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:49,583
This is-- this is
the area where the--
the hangar doors are.

739
00:34:49,750 --> 00:34:51,208
-[Lazar] Mm-hmm.
-[man] And then this is,
let's say,

740
00:34:51,375 --> 00:34:53,083
the side door, where
the mouse is here.

741
00:34:53,250 --> 00:34:57,083
And as of the f--
25th of June 2024,

742
00:34:57,541 --> 00:35:01,458
the terrain here is so, let's
